High thermal stability of CDs-ONC-ZnO hybrid films will make them a superior candidate for long-term operation that requires tolerance of temperature changes. Fig. 6
                      demonstrates the thermal decomposition of CDs-ONC, CDs-ONC-s-ZnO2, CDs-ONC-b-ZnO2 and CDs-ONC-p-ZnO2 films under an air atmosphere. The largest weight loss (nearly 80wt%) of all films were occurred between 270°C and 385°C, ascribing to the decomposition of depolymerization, dehydration and decomposition of cellulose. For CDs-ONC film, the total weight loss at approx. 650°C is ascribed to the complete decomposition of CDs-ONC. With 2wt% ZnO nanostructures introducing, a slight increasing of the thermal stability of the hybrid films could be observed. The residual weight of the three hybrid films is 2wt% at 800°C, corresponding to the addition of ZnO nanostructures. The results clearly indicate that the incorporation of ZnO nanostructures has a positive effect on the thermal degradation behavior of CDs-ONC film. A reasonable explanation is that the inorganic ZnO acts as a flame retardant by absorbing heat (Ul-Islam, Khattak, Ullah, Khanb, & Park, 2014). The comparison of thermal stability of CDs-ONC-ZnO hybrid film and PET film was performed by measuring the dimensional changes after heated at 300°C for 20min (Fig. 7
                     ). An interesting finding is that a large thermal shrinkage and wrinkle is observed from PET film (Fig. 7a and b), while the dimensional change of CDs-ONC-ZnO hybrid film is negligible (Fig. 7c and d), suggesting that CDs-ONC-ZnO hybrid films possess excellent shape stability due to their splendid thermal degradation behavior (Chun et al., 2012).
